CHAPTER XVII. Of Ne'zctrals in W'ar.

I. It may appear superfluous for us to treat of those who are extraneous to the war, since it is evident that there are no rights of war against them. But since many liberties are often taken with them, especially when they are neighbours, on the pretext of neces- sity, we may here briefly repeat what we have already said z—that Necessity, in order to give a person a right to another's property, must be of the extremest kind 3-that it is further requisite‚ that there be not a similar necessity on the pai-t of the owner 3—that even when the necessity is plain, more is not to be taken than it requires3 that is, if keeping the thing is sufficient, it is not to be used3 if using it is sufficient, it is not to be destroyed3 if destroying it is requisite, the price is to be repaid.
